<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,355,812]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,391,416]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">DIAGNOSIS:</emphasis>
Adult males are brachypterous (
<figureCitation box="[757,845,391,415]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–66" captionStartId="60.[151,264,1104,1127]" captionTargetBox="[167,1431,155,1092]" captionTargetId="figure-76@60.[167,1431,155,1148]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 65–66. Mesocapnia. 65: Habitus (live), Mesocapnia altaica, Ulastai River (MAIS2008070802); 66: Comparative distribution map. Mesocapnia silvatica not shown due to lack of georeferenced localities from historical records." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[862,891,391,415]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">67</figureCitation>
) and their average wing length is 
<quantity box="[1310,1432,391,415]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="1.25" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.0">1–1.5 mm</quantity>
. Females are also brachypterous but with longer wings than males, approximately 
<quantity box="[1102,1197,428,452]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 mm</quantity>
in length. The male epiproct usually extends to the anterior margin of tergite 9. It is relatively uniform in width (
<figureCitation box="[1187,1268,463,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
) from both the lateral and dorsal views, with a pronounced and abrupt tapering at the apex. Based on historical illustrations (Raušer 1968) (
<figureCitation box="[330,416,535,559]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
), the epiproct is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rauser" authorityYear="1968" box="[876,1011,536,560]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvatica">
<emphasis box="[876,1011,536,560]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. silvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the epiproct is shorter and wider with more gradual tapering at the apex. The female subgenital plate forms a broad triangle (
<figureCitation box="[1241,1324,572,596]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
), whereas the plates of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rauser" authorityYear="1968" box="[296,428,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvatica">
<emphasis box="[296,428,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. silvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klapalek" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[483,628,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis box="[483,628,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rounded at the apex (
<figureCitation box="[914,999,607,631]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–80" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-74@61.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 76–80. Mesocapnia variabilis. 76: Habitus (preserved); 77: Male terminalia, dorsal; 78: Male terminalia, lateral; 79: Female terminalia, ventral; 80: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
). Nymphs (
<figureCitation box="[1129,1211,607,631]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
) are indeterminable to genus or species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
