<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,355,812]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,715,740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">DISCUSSION:</emphasis>
This is the first documented occurence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1973" box="[866,982,716,740]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaica">
<emphasis box="[866,982,716,740]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. altaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1020,1132,716,740]" name="Mongolia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
. The species is endemic to the Altai Mountains for which it is named. We collected nymphs (
<figureCitation box="[890,972,751,775]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
) concurrently with adults, but these were not reared to formally confirm association with adults.
</paragraph>
